==Description== <!--T:2-->

<!--T:8-->
The '''Points Convert''' command creates point clouds from shape objects or mesh objects.

<!--T:9-->
Here a shape object refers any object with a {{PropertyData|Shape}} property. Objects created with the [[Part_Workbench|Part]] and [[PartDesign_Workbench|PartDesign]] workbench are shape objects. But so are objects created with the [[Sketcher_Workbench|Sketcher]] and [[Draft_Workbench|Draft]] workbench.

==Usage== <!--T:3-->

<!--T:10-->
# Select one or more objects.
# There are several ways to invoke the command:
#* Press the {{Button|[[Image:Points_Convert.svg|16px]] [[Points_Convert|Convert to Points]]}} button.
#* Select the {{MenuCommand|Points → [[Image:Points_Convert.svg|16px]] Convert to Points}} option from the menu.
# The {{MenuCommand|Distance}} dialog box opens.
# Enter the {{MenuCommand|maximum distance}}. The value must be in the {{Value|0.01}} - {{Value|10.00}} range.
# Press the {{Button|OK}} button to close the dialog box and finish the command.

==Properties== <!--T:11-->

<!--T:12-->
Point cloud objects are [[App_GeoFeature|App GeoFeature]] objects with the following additional properties. Select the {{MenuCommand|Show hidden}} option from the [[Property_View|Property View]] context menu to display the hidden properties.

=== Data # blender -b -P render_tubefront.py ===

=== import bpy, math ===

=== # import mesh (OBJ/FBX) ===

=== bpy.ops.import_scene.obj(filepath="/path/to/tubefront.obj") ===

=== obj = bpy.context.selected_objects[0] ===

=== # material: raw steel or painted blue ===

=== mat = bpy.data.materials.new("Coat") ===

=== mat.use_nodes = True ===

=== bsdf = mat.node_tree.nodes["Principled BSDF"] ===

=== bsdf.inputs["Base Color"].default_value = (0.06,0.33,0.85,1)  # blue ===

=== bsdf.inputs["Metallic"].default_value = 0.8 ===

=== bsdf.inputs["Roughness"].default_value = 0.25 ===

=== obj.data.materials.append(mat) ===

=== # cameras (iso/top/side) – locked positions ===

=== def add_cam(name, loc, rot): ===

===     c = bpy.data.cameras.new(name); o=bpy.data.objects.new(name,c); bpy.context.scene.collection.objects.link(o) ===

===     o.location = loc; o.rotation_euler = rot; return o ===

=== iso  = add_cam("ISO",  (3,-3,2), (math.radians(60),0,math.radians(45))) ===

=== top  = add_cam("TOP",  (0,0,5),  (math.radians(90),0,0)) ===

=== side = add_cam("SIDE", (5,0,1),  (math.radians(90),0,math.radians(-90))) ===

=== # render three PNGs with fixed naming ===

=== for cam in [iso, top, side]: ===

===     bpy.context.scene.camera = cam ===

===     bpy.context.scene.render.filepath = f"/renders/{cam.name}.png" ===

===     bpy.ops.render.render(write_still=True) ===<!--T:13-->

